description:
The domain of applications drives innovation in computer architectures and systems research. Embracing a codesign approach to the computing stack - comprising high-level algorithms, software design, and computer architectures -  where each part pushes the other and different expertise blends is the way to push the boundaries of computing knowledge.

//

The course will introduce the motivations and concepts of domain-specific architectures (DSAs) - especially highlighted from the Hennessey and Patterson Turing award lecture -, illustrating some of their key features. Case studies like Anton molecular dynamics DSA and IBM Power Edge of Network heterogeneous SoC will be presented. A spotlight on the breakthrough Artificial Intelligence domain will explore the full spectrum of domain specialization, from small chips to large-scale systems. Guest lectures from industrial researchers are already planned with partners.
One key innovation to this specialized system is the ease of hardware design. Therefore, Prof Josipovic will introduce the topic of  Computer-Aided Design (CAD) for emerging specialized accelerators, articulated into compiling software programs into circuits, provably correct circuit design, architecture-aware and low-power hardware optimizations in CAD tools, and efficient design-space exploration techniques for fast and accurate estimations.

//

The last part of the course is a simulated conference review process through a tool used in research conferences (hotcrp). Students must read manuscripts from the top venues of the field (provided by the lecturers) and review them, highlighting strengths and weaknesses. Then, in a plenary session, lecturers will moderate the program committee discussion, where students will present their pros and cons for accepting or rejecting the manuscripts to reach an agreed-upon consensus.
